04860nam a22005295i 9780822378662DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19951995ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223786627 a10.1515/97808223786622doi  a(DE-B1597)552783  a(OCoLC)1229161295  a(OCoLC)1226680158  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aDS646.27 7aHIS0480002bisacsh04a959.8/20152201 aFlorida, Nancy K., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWriting the Past, Inscribing the Future :bHistory as Prophecy in Colonial Java /cNancy K. Florida. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1995] 4cÂ©1995  a1 online resource (464 p.) :b16 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Maps and Figures -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note on Manuscripts, Spelling, Pronunciation, and Translation -- tTitles in the Kraton Surakarta -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction: On the Possibilities of Reading in Java -- tChapter 1. The Writing of a History -- tChapter 2. Babad Jaka Tingkir in Translation -- tChapter 3. Invoking the Future in Writing a Past -- tChapter 4. A Question of Visibility: Writing History in Java -- tChapter 5. The Demak Mosque: A Construction of Authority -- tChapter 6. Three Javanese Gurus: On the Generation of Marginal Powers -- tConclusion: History and Prophecy -- tAppendix 1. Descriptive Table of Contents for Kupiya Iber Warni-warni Sampeyan-dalem kaping VI -- tAppendix II. Genealogy of Sarifi Ibrahim Madyakusuma -- tAppendix III. Meters of Babad Jaka Tingkir -- tAppendix IV. Opening Lines of Cantos: Babad Jaka Tingkir -- tGlossary of Selected Terms and Titles -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLocated at the juncture of literature, history, and anthropology, Writing the Past, Inscribing the Future charts a strategy of how one might read a traditional text of non-Western historical literature in order to generate, with it, an opening for the future. This book does so by taking seriously a haunting work of historical prophecy inscribed in the nineteenth century by a royal Javanese exile-working through this writing of a colonized past to suggest the reconfiguration of the postcolonial future that this history itself apparently intends. After introducing the colonial and postcolonial orientalist projects that would fix the meaning of traditional writing in Java, Nancy K. Florida provides a nuanced translation of this particular traditional history, a history composed in poetry as the dream of a mysterious exile. She then undertakes a richly textured reading of the poem that discloses how it manages to escape the fixing of "tradition." Adopting a dialogic strategy of reading, Florida writes to extend-as the work's Javanese author demands-this history's prophetic potential into a more global register.Babad Jaka Tingkir, the historical prophecy that Writing the Past, Inscribing the Future translates and reads, is uniquely suited for such a study. Composing an engaging history of the emergence of Islamic power in central Java around the turn of the sixteenth century, Babad Jaka Tingkir was written from the vantage of colonial exile to contest the more dominant dynastic historical traditions of nineteenth-century court literature. Florida reveals how this history's episodic form and focus on characters at the margins of the social order work to disrupt the genealogical claims of conventional royal historiography-thus prophetically to open the possibility of an alternative future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 7aHISTORY / Asia / Southeast Asia.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z97831107136